This very check is rather verbose (and needs to be repeated in a few places).  You can actually do something like this to re-use the mark (https://pytest.org/latest/skipping.html#skipif):

```python

def requires_api_version(version):
    return pytest.mark.skipif(
        docker.utils.compare_version(
            version,
            docker.constants.DEFAULT_DOCKER_API_VERSION
        ) < 0,
        reason="API version too low"
    )


@requires_api_version('1.21')
def test...
```

Instead of loading this into the chain by sending a transaction, what if you instead just seeded it in the initial state.  We could alter the `chain_with_block_validation` fixtures to allow injection of extra state data.

```python
# in conftest.py
@pytest.fixture
def base_genesis_state(funded_address):
    return {...}

@pytest.fixture
def genesis_state(base_genesis_state):
    return base_genesis_state

@pytest.fixture
def chain_without_block_validation(genesis_state, ...):
    # we use the `genesis_state` here to seed the initial chain database.

# in another `test_something_about_the_evm.py` file
@pytest.fixture
def genesis_state(base_genesis_state):
    return merge(base_genesis_state, {...<custom-state-things})
```

This allows any test module to define a `genesis_state` fixture and pytest will prioritize the local one to the one in the `conftest.py` file, allowing easy injection of genesis state into those fixtures.

I think that our preferred way to do this would be as a parametrized fixture, or a parametrized test.

```
@pytest.fixture(params=[bytes, eth_keys.PrivateKey])
def private_key(request):
    return request.param(PRIVATE_KEY_BYTES)

# or

@pytest.mark.parametrize(
    'private_key',
    (
        PRIVATE_KEY_AS_BYTES,
        PRIVATE_KEY_AS_OBJ,
    ),
)
def test_the_thing(private_key):
    ...
```

